<subSubSection id="A78E3A1A6EFE5F4DA105219F47C36306" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="FB74AE002B16C6B99CEA14A5D50E4483" pageNumber="1">
[[ 
<taxonomicName id="24F868F0C216C070B8E69AA54E184677" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:020241E0-E60A-4CA8-8B8C-7502C1E70220" class="Actinopterygii" family="Blenniidae" genus="Ecsenius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ecsenius opsifrontalis Chapman &amp; Schultz 1952:521" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="opsifrontalis">Ecsenius opsifrontalis</taxonomicName>
species group]]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1DE09F2C5BA88ADD1F6C4F87EAF60965" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="0D8F340669BE42EC5369CDF5CE732473" lastPageNumber="2" pageNumber="1">
The synapomorphy that defines the 
<taxonomicName id="C442EED9C24A55A742325409370E0865" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:020241E0-E60A-4CA8-8B8C-7502C1E70220" class="Actinopterygii" family="Blenniidae" genus="Ecsenius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ecsenius opsifrontalis Chapman &amp; Schultz 1952:521" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="opsifrontalis">Opsifrontalis</taxonomicName>
species group is the presence on the body (of living or freshly dead specimens) of pinkish to reddish to brownish-orange stripes and/or bands in at least one color-pattern form of each species. These colors may be obscured by blackish stripes, bands, or spots in some species, but a faint “halo” of the color usually surrounds the dark markings.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CEF10CA3C6BBE5D6EC82272C244CE115" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="70AFC366B6590A889395EC262D52FA55" pageNumber="3">
All the species appear to be residents of coral reefs and usually are restricted to depths of under 20 m, usually under 10 m. None of the species belonging to the 
<taxonomicName id="0EB58C3088760B98974F686785E66D50" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:020241E0-E60A-4CA8-8B8C-7502C1E70220" class="Actinopterygii" family="Blenniidae" genus="Ecsenius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ecsenius opsifrontalis Chapman &amp; Schultz 1952:521" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="opsifrontalis">Opsifrontalis</taxonomicName>
group is known to occur sympatrically (Figure 1). Although reefless voids separating populations of some species (e.g., 
<taxonomicName id="DBF048DCEB68011E727B617E6EB21B53" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:2A07C7CD-F5C6-4ECA-A0A5-F0612C4F6724" class="Actinopterygii" family="Blenniidae" genus="Ecsenius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ecsenius Ecsenius fourmanoiri Springer 1972:5" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fourmanoiri">E. fourmanoiri Springer</taxonomicName>
) may be as great as 1,500 km, distances separating the same populations from that of another species in the same group (e.g., 
<taxonomicName id="D1269A8545617ADC821B8FCA8DE63B17" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BB115E5E-FE8F-4024-8DF5-D90956F26FB0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Blenniidae" genus="Ecsenius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ecsenius fijiensis Springer 1988:90" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fijiensis">E. fijiensis Springer</taxonomicName>
) may be as little as 85 km (Springer 1988:76-77).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
